answers.body_markdown:
The elements of `a` are references to `Animal`. I.e., while they may hold objects of any subclass of `Animal`, in compile-time the compiler is not aware of the exact instance that may happen to be at a specific index, so you&#39;re only allowed to use methods that exist in the `Animal` class.

If you&#39;re sure you know what instance is at a specific index (e.g., because you placed it there), you can explicitly downcast it and use the methods of that instance, e.g.:

```java
a[0] = new Dog();
((Dog)(a[0])).bark();
```

Having said that, a more idiomatic approach would be to move the declaration to a method in the abstract class:

```java
abstract class Animal{
    String name, breed, color;
    int age;

    abstract void noise();
}

class Dog extends Animal{
    void bark(){
        System.out.println(&quot;Dog:-\nwoof-woof!!!&quot;);
    }

    @Override
    public void noise() {
        bark();
    }
}
class Cat extends Animal{
    void meow(){
        System.out.println(&quot;Cat-\nmeowww!&quot;);
    }

    @Override
    public void noise() {
        meow();
    }
}
class Lion extends Animal{
    void roar(){
        System.out.println(&quot;Lion:-\nGgrrrrr!!&quot;);
    }

    @Override
    public void noise() {
        roar();
    }
}

class AnimalMain{
    public static void main(String args[]){
        Animal arr[]= new Animal[3];
        arr[0]=new Dog();
        arr[1]=new Cat();
        arr[2]=new Lion();

        for (Animal a : arr) {
            a.noise();
        }
    }
}
```

The reason for your error is that the methods bark(), meow(), and roar() are not defined in the parent class Animal, but you are trying to call them on an array of Animal objects. 

Error message gives you a hint about it:

    source_file.java:97: error: cannot find symbol
    
        a[0].bark();
    
            ^
    
      symbol:   method bark()
    
      location: class Animal


You can read it as follows: You try to call method `bark()` on a reference `a[0]`, the not found symbol (method) is `bark()` and the location (type of reference) is `class Animal`. You should look into class `Animal` to check for not found symbol `bark()`. In your code You will not find it there.

You can only call methods that are part of the objects declared type, not its actual type. To solve this, you can either define these methods in the parent class (as abstract methods if you don&#39;t want to provide a default implementation), or you can use downcasting to call these methods. Downcasting is when you cast an object of a superclass to a subclass, this allow you to call subclass specific methods.

Here is an example of how you can use downcasting:

    ((Dog) a[0]).bark();
    ((Cat) a[1]).meow();
    ((Lion) a[2]).roar();

